name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 6. 82.3% of children under the age of five in the richest wealth group had their births registered and possessed a birth certificate, only 40.7% in the poorest wealth group did. The poor (majority of whom are Muslims, STs, SCs and OBCs) will suffer the most because of this.

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: If this is used for proving citizenship or enrolment in electoral rolls, how many will get excluded? Remember, proof of citizenship requires you to not only prove that YOU were born in India but also that your parents are Indian. How will you do it when no doc is proof enough?

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 5. ~38% of kids under age of 5 don’t have birth certificates. Even among those who had their births registered, some still don’t have certificates. People who were born earlier, have even less chance of having registered births or certificates since they weren’t born in hospitals

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 4. Registration of births and deaths falls in the concurrent list. Currently states have the power to collect this data, why is this power being taken away? Why are states not opposing it?

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: The right to privacy includes the right to be protected from such acts where data is collected for one purpose (in this case, birth registration) and to use it for other purposes not expressly authorised by the person giving their data (NPR, voter enrolment, etc).

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 3. Furthermore, Puttaswamy judgement had struck down attempts to link Aadhaar with telecom and banking services. Here it is being used to expand the use of birth/death registration to Aadhaar, voter enrolment, NPR, etc.

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: This violates Article 324 of the Constitution that gives independence to ECI. It also violates the Constitution as the NPR rules are themselves unconstitutional and data should not be collected under it.

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 2. The unified database will be used for NPR-NRC, electoral rolls, passports, etc. Currently, these are all separate processes. For example, electoral roll enrolment is done by an INDEPENDENT body, ECI. Now Union govt can allow birth/death register to be used for enrolment

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: THREAD: 1. Govt wants to amend Registration of Births and Deaths Act, 1969. The amendment will allow Central govt to create a unified database of all registered births & deaths. Currently, this is carried out by states. But now Union will be allowed to collect data

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 10. Majlis will be raising this demand in the ongoing Assembly session and I’m confident that our CM will implement this scheme.

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 9. This is not an astronomical amount by any measure. We wouldn’t even need new allocation: the unutilised minority budget in the last 4 years would amount to 1800 crore. One can consider using this amount for this one-time cash transfer. 1800 crore is 1.5% of our state budget

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 8. If this is considered to be too much, at least 1% or 9000 households should be considered, which would amount to only 900 crores.

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 7. Ideally at least 18000 households should be considered for this scheme. This would amount to only ₹1800 crores as a one time expense for the state but its benefits would far outlast the expense as a whole generation could be saved from abject poverty.

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 6. Dalit Bandhu scheme provides a one-time grant of ₹10 lakh to SCs in the state. If extremely poor Muslim households are given the same amount, it would go a long way in improving their lives.

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 5. It is safe to assume that at least 1-2% of these households live in abject poverty & need urgent measures to protect them. 1% would mean 9000 households & 2% would be 18000 households.

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 3. We welcome the scheme & demand that TS govt take similar affirmative action for Muslims - not on the basis of religion but on strength of their deprivation & marginalisation  4. There are around 8.8 Muslim households in TS. CESS has estimated that ~8.5% Muslims live BPL

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: 2. However Muslims do not receive the same kind of government support as Dalits. @CMOTelangana recently started the revolutionary #DalitBandhu scheme. It’s the country’s largest cash transfer program. And visionary step by CM KCR sir

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: Strongly urge @TelanganaCMO to not extend lockdown. If goal is to reduce crowding, then we may consider evening curfews (6 PM onwards) or mini-lockdowns for COVID clusters. But expecting ~3.5cr people to live for weeks with just a 4 hour lockdown relaxation is not fair at all 4/5

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: The only long-term solution is universal vaccination. Lockdowns give a cruel choice to the poor: poverty, police atrocities or pandemic. They make a public health crisis into a law and order problem. They are neither a scientific nor a humanitarian strategy. 4/5

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: We have to accept that the pandemic is a long term reality. One can combat it only by educating the public about mask use & social distancing, and tweaking govt policies to encourage and enable such lifestyle change. 3/5

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: As data shows, COVID cases were already reducing much much before lockdown was imposed on 12th May. It's quite clear that it's not lockdown that helped. It's also clear that COVID can be combatted without lockdown 2/5

name: Asaduddin Owaisi
tweet: Telganana's Cabinet will be meeting today to discuss the extension of lockdown. I must reiterate my opposition. It's not a strategy to combat COVID-19. It APPEARS as a "hard on pandemic" strategy but all it does is destroy the lives of poor. 1/5
